                        "crm:E33_Linguistic_Object"
                    ],
                    "exact": "Allan",
                    "prefix": "\n                            \n                        \n                    \n                    \n                        \n                            \n                                \n                                    What does it mean to have—and to be known through—an archive in which postcards play such a central role? What does it mean to have risen, as Allan did, to international fame in part through this form of representation and circulation?\n                                    \n                                        \n                                            On the one hand, the postcards function as representations of",
                    "suffix": "s own mobility, their travels replicating hers and providing a visual record of the movement of white women such as Allan across national boundaries or, at any rate, out of the home or domestic space, into public, and, perversely, back again into the home, but with a different value or insidious effect"
                }
            },
