                    "exact": "Europe",
                    "prefix": " \n                                            Although this fact of mobility is implicit in every female performer’s appearance on stage, Allan again made it emphatic: her own ambiguous nationality—she was Canadian-born, American by her father’s naturalization, trained in",
                    "suffix": " and, increasingly following her success in England in 1908, British-accented, as some interviewers noted, with flashes of Americanism \n                                            \n                                                See, for instance, an interview in the Chicago Tribune on January 23, 1910, in which the interviewer notes that [a] whole-souled eastern drawl seems all the time trying to break through the shell of an English veneer"
                }
